Interesting to juxtapose the debate on creator royalties with the coming struggle of web3 product teams vs. protocol DAOs they build on top of.

If efficient markets eliminate creator royalties, what will they do to DAO fees over time?

I think it depends on power-laws...
Even collectors who value the idea of creator royalties have to make the difficult decision to contradict Mr. Market each and every time they choose to honor them.

That same logic can be applied to companies building on top of protocol DAOs they spawned

Even if you value decentralization, you may need to make the difficult decision to contradict Mr. Market each time you allows fees to flow from your users to the DAO (as opposed to the company)
If you are a power-law winning product that makes up a majority of the userbase of a protocol, Mr. Market likely tells you not to share the value your company is creating with the DAO.

If there is more competition, resulting in a more normal distribution of products on top of the protocol, its more likely Mr. Market tells you the rational thing to do is keep building on top of the protocol--and even pay its fees (assuming they're minimally extractive)

An implication for protocols is that they need to carefully consider how to grow integrations and competition of their complements—the products on top, in order to achieve that more normal distribution.

Stoked to announce the most recent Variant-led seed:
https://variant.fund/articles/modulus-zero-knowledge-machine-learning-seed-round/
To date, AI has been a centralizing technology—most models run on private, centralized systems that are opaque to end users.
In crypto, a world where verification is paramount, and computation is expensive, current machine learning models simply don't meet the cut

Modulus is bridging this gap with zkML, which uses zero-knowledge cryptography to prove that the computation done by machine learning models was done correctly, extending the trust assumptions expected from  smart contracts to offchain models.

As  wrote in 2014 about DAOs: “automation at the center, humans at the edges.” 

In that spirit, zkML allows AI to be  at the center of decentralized protocols, to automate manual processes often coordinated by humans today.

I think crypto uniquely enables a barbell of new software-based projects:

One one end, I think we'll see networks that are way bigger/more valuable than web2 platforms, because they're permissionless and decentralized, and everyone can integrate them (e.g Internet Money, Uniswap, etc.)

On the other end, we'll see many projects that couldn't exist, because they were too niche/small, didn't make sense in the traditional VC model. These projects can be funded/owned/operated by users, at cost, or close to it. 

I think some of these can still be good investments, but entry price has to be low.

On succesful crypto companies, most important quality is founders that are laser focused, e.g. , , hayden, etc. 

On succesful crypto networks, I think the most important quality is technical writing as a storytelling tool for inspiration, e.g. , satoshi
On acquisition/retention in crypto, the new tool in the toolkit is tokens. I think they have been overused for acquisition and under-used for retention.
